flowRoot.flowPara: Rich Miller, data mostly from Knopp & Cormier, Arbona, 8/20/2015

Codes: D-drift (submerged), A-accidental, B-behavioral, M-migrate, X-eclose (escape from final nymphal skin), E-emerge (through the film or onto the bank), F-float (on surface), O-oviposit, followed by loc or time indicator in parens. Starred-more important to fishers.
† E times move away from the hottest part of the day in summer, toward it in early and late season.
‡ Dun drift times decrease in hotter weather.

ARBONA'S PRINCIPLES: 1) Insect MORPHOLOGY and BEHAVIOR (including the WHERE and WHAT of AVAILABILITY are determined at the FAMILY level. Together, these set the useful fly PATTERNS and fishing TECHNIQUES. 2) Insect SIZE and COLOR are determined at the GENUS, sometimes the SPECIES level. These set fly SIZE and DRESSING.

MAYFLY AVAILABILITY is tightly bound to emergence since the nymphs usually become active just hours before the duns eclose, and the spinners fall within a day or two after. Prior to emergence, nymphs are only available during normal activity (esp swimming) or accidental or behavoiral drift.

UNLESS there are special behaviors, you don't need to identify below family -- just capture and match pattern, color and size. However, you can use color descriptions to both confirm and predict. Eg, if you know the nymph, you know how to imitate the dun and spinner.

There are two distinct modes of emergence, one where the number of days on any given reach is short, but rolls upriver, and to other higher waters, and the other where the emergence remains in place, often day after day (with missed days due to poor conditions) for months. I depict the latter with broken timelines. These are likely due to asynchronous, as opposed (or, in addition) to multvoltine biology.

In the first mode, where I can find the data, the timelines are highlighted to show timing and duration of the important part of the emergence on the water named first (which should be the earliest major one in California of that bug) or in bold.
WHEN ONSET TEMP is given, you can use it to re-estimate the tabulated seasonal emergence timings for particular stretches of water, possibly for all the bugs.

tspan.tspan: Best in spring crks (alkaline), really need to get hook size right.
1-2wk span, but not every night, daily 30-45min, fish nymphs first.
Lower rivs, follow D.grandis, higher waters more spor, 1, sometimes 2yr devel, fish the nymphs.
E usu 1 hr, but much longer if overcast, hot days may be skipped entirely.
